 of new comparative studies in modernism. The book's central claim is that modernist Hebrew prose-fiction, as it emerged from 1900 to 1930, was shaped by the highly charged encounter of traditionally educated Jews with the revolution of European literature and culture known as modernism. The book deals with modernist Hebrew fiction as an urban phenomenon, explores the ways in which the genre dealt with issues of sexuality and gender, and examines its depictions of the complex relations between tradition, modernity, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHebrew fictionxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxEurope. 0aHebrew fictionzEuropey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish fictionxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxEurope. 0aJewish fictionzEuropey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804777247zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777247.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles